\ltrpar\ql\rtlch\af1\afs24\ltrch\f2\fs24 {\highlight7 <CH1>}{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*1>}1{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}According to the Talmud, a vow is when one says that such is forbidden to me as is—a {\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'f7\'c8\'f8\'c0\'e1\'cc\'c8\'ef{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch , 
a sacrifice. In place of the word korban, the word konom was frequently used. There is a dispute 
in Maseches Nedarim as to the origin of the word.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*2>}2{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}The vow to fast is made at the Mincha service of the day preceding the fast day.\par
{\highlight7 <CH2>}{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*1>}1{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}“Keeping dishes warm” means that we are permitted to place cooked foods on a covered 
stove in order to preserve their heat. An example of this is the traditional Cholent.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*2>}2{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}The Rav of the community usually includes the community in his eiruv. This can be done 
however by anyone. It is done by handing over the cooked food to another person through whom 
he grants a share of the food (of the eiruv) to the entire community. This person raises the eiruv 
a tefach, (handsbreadth) and returns it to the one making the eiruv.\par
{\highlight7 <CH5>}{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*1>}1{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Shabbos, more than other days, lends itself to offering praise and thanksgiving to Hashem. 
When man rests from his physical labor and is relieved of material concerns, his soul is free to 
pursue the intellectual and spiritual aspects of life. These pursuits lead him to serve Hashem and 
to praise Him.—Radak\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*2>}2{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}We will proclaim His kindliness in the morning of redemption. And while yet in the 
darkness of exile we proclaim our belief in His faithfulness.—Rashi\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*3>}3{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}The Shabbos day of rest affords me the opportunity to observe and appreciate the greatness 
of Your work.—Radak\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*4>}4{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Hashem’s ‘works’ are the visible creation, while His ‘thoughts’ are the Divine purpose 
behind each created thing.—Seporno\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*5>}5{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Others translate, ‘You have increased my might like that of the wild ram.’\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*6>}6{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}The palm and the cedar both enjoy a long life span and flourish during all seasons. Thus 
they symbolize the lasting happiness of the righteous in contrast to the short prosperity of the 
wicked.\par
{\highlight7 <CH6>}{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*1>}1{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}These are the gates of sunrise and sunset through which Hashem, in His infinite wisdom, 
has divided life on earth into two complementary halves.—Rabbi S.R. Hirsch\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*2>}2{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}He alternates the three daily periods—evening, morning, and afternoon.—Avudraham\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*3>}3{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}The stars appear as watchmen appointed by Hashem to stand guard over the sleeping 
world below. He also appointed them their places in definite orbits according to His will and for 
purposes known to Him alone.—S.R. Hirsch\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*4>}4{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}His Name {\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'e4' \'f6\'c0\'e1\'c8\'e0\'e5\'c9\'fa{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch  means “He Who takes all the infinite variety of hosts and creatures and 
unites them to act and interact as parts of one unified Universe.—S.R. Hirsch\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*5>}5{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}This prayer is an abbreviated form of the {\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'e0\'c7\'e4\'c2\'e1\'c8\'e4 \'f8\'c7\'e1\'cc\'c8\'e4{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch  prayer in the morning service. It thanks 
Hashem for the sacred gift of Divine Revelation that He granted Yisrael. It declares that Torah 
alone is the eternal heritage of the Jewish people and that all other goods and gifts of life are 
transitory.—S.R. Hirsch\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*6>}6{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}All that we have affirmed in the Shema, is true and trustworthy.—Etz Yosef\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*7>}7{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}He redeemed us from Pharaoh, and saved us from Sichon and Og in the days of Moshe and 
from the thirtyone kings in the days of Yehoshua.—Etz Yosef\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*8>}8{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}“Tyrants” include Amalek and others who wanted to destroy us.—Etz Yosef\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*9>}9{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}The Malbim says that “oppressors” ({\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'f6\'c8\'f8\'c5\'e9\'f0\'e5\'cc{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch ) refers to those who actively persecute us whereas 
“enemies” ({\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'e0\'e5\'c9\'e9\'c0\'e1\'c5\'e9\'f0\'e5\'cc{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch ) refers to those who would rejoice over our misfortune without necessarily 
contributing to our downfall in an outright manner.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*10>}10{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}“Great things” refers to the way Hashem rules according to the laws of nature and 
“wonders” refers to those things that are classified as miracles.—Siach Yitzchak\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*11>}11{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Not only does Hashem sustain our souls in exile but He also sustains our physical 
wellbeing.—Siach Yitzchak\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*12>}12{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}The redemption from Egypt is the source for all later redemptions; it is the source from 
which our final and total salvation will spring. We became free, never again to taste the bitterness 
of spiritual or physical bondage.—Sfas Emes\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*13>}13{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Shemos 15:11\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*14>}14{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Shemos 15:2\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*15>}15{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Shemos 15:18\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*16>}16{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Yirmiyahu 31:10\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*17>}17{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Undisturbed peace, and strength for a new day of vigorous living are the gifts that night 
brings and for which we pray to Hashem.—S.R. Hirsch\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*18>}18{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}We particularly ask of Him at night to bless us with wise counsel. Daytime is the time for 
achievement, but the rest that comes with nightfall is made to allow man to compose his thoughts. 
By virtue of the complete relaxation it affords, sleep endows the mind and spirit with renewed 
vigor. We pray therefore for Divine aid so that our nightly rest will help us take wise counsel and 
affirm worthy resolution for future days.—Avudraham and Siach Yitzchak\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*19>}19{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Shield us from trouble before it comes, and remove it from us if it has already come.—Siach 
Yitzchak\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*20>}20{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}The Hebrew word {\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'f9\'d2\'c8\'e8\'c8\'ef{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch  (Satan) used in the Prayer Book refers to the Evil Impulse, the lower 
passions which are a hindrance to man’s pursuit of the nobler aims in life. It is against the 
dominance of this impulse that the Jew prays. The “adversary,” therefore, is any person, spirit, or 
Evil Impulse that seduces us to do wrong.—Dover Sholom and others\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*21>}21{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Shemos 31:16±17. This is merely metaphorical, since Hashem of course does not become 
tired, nor does He require rest.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*22>}22{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}The Talmud (Rosh Hashana 8a) relates the word {\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'eb\'cc\'c6\'f1\'c6\'e4{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch  to {\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'eb\'cc\'c0\'f1\'c9\'e4{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch , covering. All the festivals occur 
when the moon is clearly visible. Rosh Hashana occurs at the beginning of the month when the 
moon is still covered.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*23>}23{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Tehillim 81:4±5.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*24>}24{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Rabbi Yonasan Eibschitz in his sefer, Yaaros Devash, explains that upon reflecting in 
Whose presence he is about to pray, man should be so overwhelmed with awe and trepidation 
that he is unable to open his lips. He therefore prefaces his prayer by beseeching Hashem, to open 
his lips, asking His help to be able to pray in His Presence.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*25>}25{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Because these are days of judgment and our lives hang in the balance, we pray to Hashem 
to remember us for life (Rashi, Levush).\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*26>}26{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}This is based on Yechezkel 18:32, ‘For I do not desire the death of him that dies, but rather 
that he repent from his evil ways and live.’\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*27>}27{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}This refers to the Book in which the righteous are inscribed for life everlasting.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*28>}28{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}We ask Hashem to grant us life for His sake, i.e., so that we can fulfill His commandments.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*29>}29{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}We proclaim and accept His kingship on Rosh Hashana.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*30>}30{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}He helps us during the Ten Days of Penitence, by accepting our repentance.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*31>}31{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}He delivers us on Yom Kippur by forgiving our sins.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*32>}32{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Hashem’s rule of the world is permanent and perpetual (Kuzari).\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*33>}33{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Here we emphatically declare our belief in the immortality of the soul (Kuzari).\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*34>}34{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Deliverance is not a sudden happening but rather a process of growth or sprouting.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*35>}35{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Even if we are not worthy of life by virtue of our deeds, inscribe us for life because You are 
a merciful Father (Siddur Chasidei Ashkenaz).\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*36>}36{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}The word {\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'e5\'cc\'e1\'c0\'eb\'c5\'ef{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch , ‘and so,’ marks the beginning of the special prayers of the Shemoneh Esreh 
recited at each Rosh Hashana and Yom Kippur service. According to Avudraham, the Sages chose 
this word to convey the thought expressed by Esther as she prepared to go before the king on 
behalf of her people. After telling Mordechai to assemble all the Jews to fast for three days and 
nights on her behalf, she said, “ {\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'e5\'cc\'e1\'c0\'eb\'c5\'ef \'e0\'c8\'e1\'e5\'c9\'e0 \'e0\'c6\'ec \'e4\'c7\'ee\'cc\'c6\'ec\'c6\'ea\'c0{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch  ‘and so I will go in to the king” (Esther 4:16). Thus, 
since today is the Day of Judgment, as we come before the Supreme King of kings, the Holy One 
Blessed is He, we begin with the words uttered by Esther as she came before the king. The Siddur 
Maggid Tzedek quoted by Siach Yitzchak writes that the emphasis of Avudraham was on the last 
words of the verse said by Esther, “{\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'e5\'cc\'e1\'c0\'eb\'c5\'ef \'e0\'c8\'e1\'e5\'c9\'e0 \'e0\'c6\'ec \'e4\'c7\'ee\'cc\'c6\'ec\'c6\'ea\'c0 \'e0\'c2\'f9\'d1\'c6\'f8 \'ec\'c9\'e0 \'eb\'c7\'e3\'cc\'c8\'fa{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch ,” “And so I will go into the king, 
even if it is unlawful,” for which one of us can say, “I am virtuous, I have cleansed my heart from 
sin.” Especially on this great and awesome Day of Judgment, who among us is not embarrassed 
and ashamed to appear before the King of kings garbed in sackcloths of sin. If Esther who had 
fasted for three days in penitence and prayer in preparation for her appearance before the king 
was nevertheless so terribly frightened that she declared: “{\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'e5\'cc\'e1\'c0\'eb\'c5\'ef \'e0\'c8\'e1\'e5\'c9\'e0 \'e0\'c6\'ec \'e4\'c7\'ee\'cc\'c6\'ec\'c6\'ea\'c0 \'e0\'c2\'f9\'d1\'c6\'f8 \'ec\'c9\'e0 \'eb\'c7\'e3\'cc\'c8\'fa{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch ” then we 
should certainly tremble in awe before the presence of Hashem on this Day of Judgment, knowing 
deep in our hearts how little and how poorly we have prepared ourselves. Thus our Sages 
ordained that we open the prayers with the word {\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'e5\'cc\'e1\'c0\'eb\'c5\'ef{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch  recalling the words of Esther; therewith 
shattering our delusiouns of spiritual complacency, and causing us to bow before Him with 
broken hearts and tearfilled eyes.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*37>}37{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}The word {\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'fa\'cc\'c5\'ef{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch  implies {\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'ee\'c7\'fa\'cc\'c8\'f0\'c8\'e4{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch , a gift. We ask Hashem to grant us the feeling of reverence for 
Him, as a gift, knowing how difficult it is to attain such a high level of reverence completely on 
our own (Siach Yitzchak).\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*38>}38{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}The word {\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'ee\'c7\'f2\'c2\'f9\'d2\'c6\'e9\'ea\'c8{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch , lit., Your works, indicates that which has attained or is near perfection. 
Thus Yisrael is called His works since we have accepted His kingship and His Torah which is the 
fulfillment of Hashem’s creation (Siach Yitzchak).\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*39>}39{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}All you have created, {\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'f9\'d1\'c6\'e1\'cc\'c8\'f8\'c8\'e0\'fa\'c8{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch , indicates that which has not attained its fulfillment, thus we 
ask Hashem to cast His dread even on those people who have not yet accepted His Divine 
Kingdom (Siach Yitzchak).\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*40>}40{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}The nation of Yisrael will fear You.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*41>}41{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}The nations of the world will finally prostrate themselves before You, i.e. submit to You 
and accept the yoke of Your Kingship.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*42>}42{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Once all of Your works and created beings have submitted themselves to Your rule and 
formed a single bond to do Your will, the honor of Yisrael will be established and raised to new 
heights. It will then be apparent to all that Yisrael alone carried the yoke of Hashem’s kingdom 
throughout the bitter years of exile, giving Him obedience despite its suffering and persecution 
and the taunts of those who cynically asked, “Where is Your God” (Etz Yosef).\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*43>}43{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Those who fear Hashem will then be praiseworthy in the eyes of all men.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*44>}44{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Men will no longer consider as ridiculous those who seek Hashem and search for ways to 
serve Him.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*45>}45{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Those who wait upon Him will no longer be subdued but will voice their convictions 
freely.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*46>}46{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}See Tehillim 132:17. The climax of this spiritual renaissance will be the restoration of our 
people to our land under the scepter of the Moshiach, descendant of Dovid, the anointed of 
Hashem.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*47>}47{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}The entire universe was created for the sake of Yisrael in order that Hashem’s Divine 
Influence be attached to it. This essence (Yisrael) was created for the sake of an even more 
treasured essence, namely the prophets and the pious among them. This gradation forms the basis 
of the sequence of the Rosh Hashana±Yom Kippur prayers: “Grant that Your awe be upon all that 
You have made,” is the first prayer. It is followed by, “Grant honor to Your people,” and finally 
by “the righteous will see this and rejoice.” Thus the righteous and pious are the purpose and 
fulfillment of the entire creation, the true reason for celebrating these holy days (Fundamentals of 
Kuzari, page 59).\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*48>}48{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Our plea to Hashem is, “let Your rule become evident in all Your glory.” Hashem has 
reigned supreme at all times; it is only man who, until now, has failed to recognize Hashem’s rule 
and render Him homage. We now pray that man will at long last come to know Hashem’s eternal, 
universal sovereignty and pay it the tribute of unreserved obedience (S.R. Hirsch).\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*49>}49{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}According to Avudraham this classification refers to the very wicked who have never 
fulfilled a commandment, but who nevertheless have breath in their nostrils. Let them also 
proclaim on the Day of Judgment, that You, God of Yisrael are King!\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*50>}50{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Even as Hashem Himself is forever true, and even as His word, the Torah and the promise 
revealed to us are eternally true and unalterable, so too our own service to Him should be true, 
unswerving and constant. For this purpose we pray for {\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'e8\'c7\'e4\'c2\'f8\'c7\'fa \'e4\'c7\'ec\'cc\'c5\'e1{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch , purity of heart. We must cleanse 
and purify our hearts of every passion and impulse that might tempt us to transgress the law or 
that might stand in the way of our serving Hashem (S.R. Hirsch).\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*51>}51{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Rav S.R. Hirsch’s translates, “Adonoy is the source of my life’s strength,” thus Dovid 
declares that Hashem is the fount from which his life derives its power to resist all foes.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*52>}52{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Dovid says that he trusts in the declaration stated in the opening verse, “Adonoy is my 
light and my salvation; whom shall I fear?”—Rashi, Radak\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*53>}53{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}The literal translation of {\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'f9\'d1\'c4\'e1\'c0\'fa\'cc\'c4\'e9{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch  is “my sitting.” The Talmud states that “no man may ‘sit’ in 
the courtyard of the Temple except for the kings of the House of Dovid.—Maseches Soteh 40b\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*54>}54{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}The Vilna Gaon comments that the commandment of Succos is implied in this verse and 
the next.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*55>}55{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Dovid declares, “Because I look up to Hashem in every aspect of my existence, I am so 
exalted that no enemy can harm me.—S.R. Hirsch\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*56>}56{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}This verse alludes to Rosh Hashana and Yom Kippur. “Hear my voice,” refers to Rosh 
Hashana when we sound the shofar. The word “my voice (sound)” refers to the “voice” of the 
shofar. “When I call” refers to Yom Kippur, about which Yeshaya (55:6) said, “call to Him when 
He is near.”—Siddur HaGra\par
