tearing his flesh with iron hooks, “All my life, I have longed for this moment. I have loved 
Hashem with all my heart and with all my might; and now at last, I can love Him with my whole 
life.” It was this concept that gave Jewish martyrs the courage to lay down their lives for their 
faith.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*61>}61{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}The Sages (ibid.) explain, “With whatever lot Providence has assigned to you,” i.e., despite 
whatever material sacrifice your loyalty to Hashem and to Torah might entail.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*62>}62{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}The teachings of the Torah should be ever fresh in your minds, as though you received it 
today.—Ibid.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*63>}63{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}See to it that your children have a clear, and not a confused, stammering knowledge of the 
Torah.—Ibid.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*64>}64{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Devarim 6:5±9. This paragraph contains 10 commandments: 1) accepting the “yoke” of 
heaven; 2) proclaiming the Unity of Hashem; 3) loving Hashem; 4) studying Torah (and you shall 
speak of them); 5) teaching your children; 6±7) reciting Shema in the evening and in the morning; 
8±9) putting on the tefillin of the hand and head; 10) putting up mezuzos on the door posts.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*65>}65{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}The service of the heart is prayer, as Dovid said (Tehillim 141:2) “May my prayers be 
acceptable to You as an incense [service].”\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*66>}66{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Hashem will make it rain at night so as not to cause you discomfort.—Rashi\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*67>}67{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Reward and punishment are here connected with the rainfalls vital to the Land of Yisrael. 
The heavy rains which open the growing season in the fall and the showers which fall while the 
grain is ripening are of utmost importance.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*68>}68{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}One who is satisfied can easily be induced to forget the Source of his fullness.—Rashi\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*69>}69{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}No extension will be given. The “generation of the flood” was granted a reprieve of 120 
years (Bereishis 6:3) because they did not have from whom to learn; but you do have from whom 
to learn.—Sifrei, cited by Rashi\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*70>}70{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Even in exile you must fulfill Hashem’s commandments—Sifrei cited by Rashi\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*71>}71{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Between your eyes is not to be taken literally. The correct position of the phylactery of the 
head (shel rosh) is at the edge of the hair line directly above the place which is between the eyes.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*72>}72{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}From the moment your son knows how to talk, begin teaching him the Torah.—Rashi.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*73>}73{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Rabbi Yehuda bar Chaviva said that this third section was added to Shema because of six 
important things contained therein: 1. the commandment of fringes, 2. mention of the Exodus, 
3.{\highlight7 <TIE>}the call to assume the yoke of Hashem’s commandments, 4. the warning against heretical 
concepts, 5. the warning against straying after sinful desires, and 6. the warning against 
idolatrous worship.—Maseches Berachos 12b\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*74>}74{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Rabbi Meir says: “the blue thread of the fringes resembles the sea, the sea reflects the 
heavens, and heavens resemble the Throne of Glory” (Sifrei). The outward act of looking upon 
the tzitzis leads the Jew to inward spiritual conformity with the precepts of Hashem.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*75>}75{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}The heart and the eyes of a person are the agents of sin—the eye sees, the heart desires, and 
thus the person sins.—Tanchuma cited by Rashi.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*76>}76{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Bamidbar 15:37±41.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*77>}77{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}The Jew declares his commitment to Hashem, and states that His precepts are not forced 
upon him. On the contrary, they are beloved, cherished, delightful and pleasant to him.—Siach 
Yitzchak\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*78>}78{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}The teachings of Torah are correct in their totality. They lack nothing and are eternally 
valid for all situations.—Siach Yitzchak\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*79>}79{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Even those precepts that are not easily understood and appear to contradict human nature, 
are accepted by us.—Siach Yitzchak\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*80>}80{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}All that was affirmed above in Shema.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*81>}81{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}After having affirmed that all that was said in Shema is true, firm, certain, enduring, etc., 
