been lowly captives in Egypt.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*88>}88{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Hashem also helps those who are spiritually impoverished.—Rabbi Yehuda ben Yakar\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*89>}89{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Intrinsically.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*90>}90{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}By others.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*91>}91{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}As it is said, “{\highlight7 <MS>}‘And a redeemer will come to Tziyon and to those of Yaakov who repent of 
their transgression,’ said Adonoy” (Yeshaya 59:20).\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*92>}92{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}While Hashem is always referred to as the Redeemer of Yisrael, this blessing utilizes the 
past tense, “Who redeemed Yisrael,” as it refers specifically to our redemption from 
Egypt.—Tzelosa d’Avraham\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}Our faith in the Redeemer of Yisrael Who redeemed us from Egypt, and our hope that He will 
