\ltrch (drink) and {\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'ec\'c0\'e5\'c4\'e9\'c8\'e4{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch  (escort), which were part of the generous hospitality provided by Avraham.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*15>}15{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}The true prophet must be genuinely tov “good” and a friend to all men both in his attitude 
and in his conduct. The heart of a true prophet in Yisrael must be capable of genuine rejoicing 
when individuals and mankind flourish, and of sincere sorrow when they go into decline. The 
Jewish prophet stands in the service of tov of the kingdom of the absolute good whose messanger 
he is meant to be.—S.R. Hirsch\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*16>}16{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}The prophet is given only the basic content of the ideals which he is to proclaim. The words 
in which he expresses the theme communicated to him however, are his own. According to the 
Sages {\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'e0\'c5\'e9\'ef \'f9\'d1\'c0\'f0\'c5\'e9 \'f0\'c0\'e1\'c4\'e9\'e0\'c4\'e9\'ed \'ee\'c4\'fa\'c0\'f0\'c7\'e1\'cc\'c0\'e0\'c4\'e9\'ef \'e1\'cc\'c0\'f1\'c4\'e2\'c0\'f0\'e5\zwj\'c9\'ef \'e0\'c6\'e7\'c8\'e3{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch , each prophet has a style, peculiar to him alone, hence a 
prophet requires the gift of eloquence. Hashem chooses as His prophets only such men whose 
words are {\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'f0\'c6\'e0\'c1\'ee\'c8\'f8\'c4\'e9\'ed \'e1\'cc\'c6\'e0\'c1\'ee\'c6\'fa{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch , spoken in truth.—S. R. Hirsch\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*17>}17{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}This refers to the armies of Egypt and Amalek.—Rashi\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*18>}18{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}This refers to the fruits of the fourth year after planting which must be eaten in 
Yerushalayim or redeemed with money. The money is then spent in Yerushalayim on 
foodstuff.—Metsudas Dovid\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*19>}19{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}This refers to Babylonia.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*20>}20{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Weeping in this sense indicated that they will be moved to tears by their prayers and 
repentance.—Rashi\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*21>}21{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}During the Exile, the Kohanim were deprived of their share of the sacrifices and tithes. 
Upon the deliverance of the people, they will again receive their due.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*22>}22{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}The sinner regrets the sins of the past.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*23>}23{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}This is the People of Yisrael, which is humiliated in exile. According to Avudraham and 
the siddur of Rav Amram Gaon, the text reads: {\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'e5\'c0\'ec\'c7\'f2\'c2\'e2\'e5\'cc\'ee\'c7\'fa \'f0\'c6\'f4\'c6\'f9\'d1{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch  which would mean “the one whose 
soul is grieved.”\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*24>}24{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}“Stranger” in this context means anyone not of the seed of Dovid.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*25>}25{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Others translate {\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'f0\'c0\'e4\'e5\'c9\'f8\'c8\'e0 \'ee\'c7\'f2\'c7\'ec\'c0\'e9\'c8\'e0{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch  as “higher (or true) enlightenment.”\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*26>}26{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}The Sages often use the word {\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'eb\'cc\'c7\'ec\'c5\'e9{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch  in reference to Agadic lectures, and thus {\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'f8\'c5\'e9\'f9\'d1\'c5\'e9 \'eb\'c7\'ec\'c5\'e9{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch  would 
be translated as the chief lecturers, ({\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'e3\'c7\'f8\'c0\'f9\'d1\'c8\'f0\'c4\'e9\'ed{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch ). Torah assemblies {\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'eb\'cc\'c7\'ec\'c5\'e9{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch  were held during the months of 
Adar and Elul in order to inspire the people and instruct them concerning the approaching 
holidays of Pesach, the High Holidays, and Sukkos.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*27>}27{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Judges used to hold court within the gates.\par
{\highlight7 <CH15>}{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*1>}1{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}According to Rashi, this psalm urges the nations of the world to join hands in recognizing 
the sovereignty of the Almighty.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*2>}2{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}The words {\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'e4\'c8\'f8\'c4\'e9\'f2\'e5\'cc \'ec\'c5\'e0\'ec\'c9\'e4\'c4\'e9\'ed{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch  may also be translated, “sound blasts of the horn unto Hashem.” The 
Malbim notes that it is customary to sound trumpets during a royal coronation ceremony. This is 
what the nations will do when they proclaim Hashem as their King. (See Rav Saadiah Gaon’s first 
reason for the shofar on Rosh Hashana.)\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*3>}3{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}The pride of Yaakov refers to the Holy Temple which is our inheritance, and wherein 
Hashem’s spirit resides in glorious splendor.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*4>}4{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}According to Midrash this verse alludes to the blast of the Shofar on Rosh Hashana, and 
specifically to the sound of {\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'fa\'cc\'c0\'f8\'e5\'cc\'f2\'c8\'e4{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch , teruah, the broken blast which symbolizes the harsh, shattering 
punishment of Elokim, He Who rules with strict justice. When the Jew hears the broken notes of 
the teruah, he realizes that he deserves shattering punishment for his transgressions and is 
inspired to teshuvah, true repentance. His sins are forgiven and this forgiveness is symbolized in 
the ascendance of Hashem from His Throne of Strict Justice (Elokim) to sit on His Throne of 
Mercy. Thus Hashem ascends because of the teruah sound of the shofar.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*5>}5{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Even ordinary people are urged to clap hands and call out to Hashem with joyous song 
(verse 2), but the art of singing praises to Hashem is reserved for the {\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'ee\'c7\'f9\'d2\'c0\'eb\'cc\'c4\'e9\'ec{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch , one who is skillful and 
of superior intelligence.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*6>}6{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Rabbeinu Yonah says that the {\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'f0\'c0\'e3\'c4\'e9\'e1\'c5\'e9 \'f2\'c7\'ee\'c4\'e9\'ed{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch  refers to the heads of the twelve tribes of Yisrael, for 
the twelve tribes are called nations (see Devarim 33:19).\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*7>}7{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Hashem has the power to shield those who trust in Him (Rashi).\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*8>}8{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}The Psalmist does not say that the people who hear the call of teruah but rather those who 
understand the call of teruah, are fortunate. Those who understand the intrinsic power of teruah 
which inspires man to repent are truly fortunate.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*9>}9{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}The Radak says that the man who is spiritually aroused by the blast of the teruah, perceives 
Divine truths which illuminate his path and keep him from stumbling.\par
{\highlight7 <CH16>}{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*1>}1{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}When saying the words, “{\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'ec\'c0\'ee\'c7\'f2\'c7\'f0\'c0\'ea\'c8 \'e0\'c6\'ec\'c9\'f7\'c4\'e9\'ed \'e7\'c7\'e9\'c4\'e9\'ed{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch ,” “for Your sake living God,” you might offer this 
silent prayer: Master of the Universe, because we believe in the absolute unity of Your Name, that 
You alone are the living God, and there is nothing besides You, it is fitting and proper that You 
inscribe us in the Book of Life.—Yesod V’shoresh HaAvodah\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*2>}2{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}The Divine deliverance of our people will not come about in a sudden, dramatic fashion, but 
rather as a gradual development, as a plant that sprouts forth in stages.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*3>}3{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}The Chasam Sofer says that {\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'e6\'e5\zwj\'c9\'eb\'c5\'f8 \'e9\'c0\'f6\'e5\'cc\'f8\'c8\'e9\'e5 \'ec\'c0\'e7\'c7\'e9\'c4\'e9\'ed \'e1\'cc\'c0\'f8\'c7\'e7\'c2\'ee\'c4\'e9\'ed{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch  does not mean that we ask Hashem to 
remember us for life in His mercy, but rather that He grant us {\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'e7\'c7\'e9\'c4\'e9\'ed \'f9\'d1\'c6\'ec \'f8\'c7\'e7\'c2\'ee\'c4\'e9\'ed{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch , a life of mercy, a life 
in which we will exemplify the quality and virtue of compassion.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*4>}4{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}When saying these sentences, bear in mind these words: “How long has Your great, sacred 
Name been desecrated among the nations as they taunt us, asking, “Where is Your God? Why 
doesn’t He come to your aid?” Therefore, let Your awe be upon all Your works, Your dread upon 
all You have created, so they may all know there is no God but You, and thus will Your Name be 
exalted and sanctified even among the nations.—Yesod V’Shoresh HaAvodah\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*5>}5{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}The ultimate sanctification of Hashem’s great and holy Name over the nation of Yisrael will 
have a tremendous impact on all peoples and will result in their spiritual uplifting for they will 
be inspired to fear Hashem, and subject themselves to His rule.—R’ Moshe Chaim Luzzato, 
(Yalkut Yedeos HaEmes)\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*6>}6{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}The Divine inspiration of Hashem, Who is One, the Unity par excellence, can only be 
experienced by an entity, united, in a single cause. The nation of Yisrael, though composed of 
individuals, is nevertheless a unit, bound by its singular belief in Hashem and Torah. Thus we are 
referred to as {\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'e2\'e5\'c9\'e9 \'e0\'c6\'e7\'c8\'e3 \'e1\'cc\'c8\'e0\'c8\'f8\'c6\'f5{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch  one nation in the land, and as such, we are capable of receiving and 
retaining the Divine influence. The nations of the world however are many, and the diversity 
within each nation is great. In their present status they are incapable of experiencing the Divine 
inspiration. We pray, therefore, for the time when they will attach themselves to the nation of 
Yisrael, and recognize the superiority of our moral and spiritual values. Then, they will attain a 
level of unity and be capable of receiving a degree of Divine enlightenment. This is the intent of 
our prayer, “and may they all form a single band.”—R’ Moshe Chaim Luzzato, Ibid.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*7>}7{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Those who understand and recognize the mysterious ways in which Hashem rules the 
world, realize that despite superficial events that seem to indicate otherwise, Hashem’s rule is 
indisputable and all powerful. Thus we declare our firm belief in His rulership and His 
strength.—R’ Moshe Chaim Luzzato, Ibid\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*8>}8{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Despite our status as a chosen and holy people, only when the entire world reaches its 
ultimate perfection, will we achieve our ultimate goal. Thus only after Hashem’s kingdom is 
revealed in the world, and good triumphs over evil, will we reach our maximum potential and 
thereby bask in His glory. This is our prayer, “grant honor, Almighty, to Your people.”—R. 
Moshe Chaim Luzzato, Ibid.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*9>}9{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}The only setting for this glorious fulfillment is in the Holy Land—there in the chosen land, 
will the chosen people experience its true spiritual fulfillment, under the leadership of the king, a 
descendant of the chosen house of royalty, the house of Dovid.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*10>}10{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}The literal translation of {\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'f7\'c6\'f8\'c6\'ef{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch  is horn, but it is often translated pride because the horn is the 
pride of the animal.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*11>}11{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}According to Pri Tzadik, the righteous are those who serve Hashem with meticulous 
observance of Torah and Mitzvos even without experiencing the inner joy and radiance of serving 
Him. They will therefore be privileged to see and rejoice in the time to come.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*12>}12{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}The upright are those whose hearts are filled with joy at serving their Creator through the 
fulfillment of Torah and Mitzvos. They will therefore be jubilant at the revelation of Hashem’s 
kingdom.—Pri Tzadik\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*13>}13{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}The pious are those whose attachment to Hashem is so great that they serve Him in ways 
which are even beyond and above the precisely ordained commands of the Torah. They will be 
privileged to exult in joyous song at the time to come.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*14>}14{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}The terms, injustice, all wickedness and rule of evil refer to Amalek, the archenemy of the 
Jewish people and of Hashem. Its name and memory will ultimately be obliterated from the 
earth.—R’ Moshe Chaim Luzzato\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*15>}15{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}And thus will begin the kingdom of Hashem on earth, which is the ultimate goal of man’s 
development through the ages and which centers forever in Yerushalayim and Tziyon.—S.R. 
Hirsch\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*16>}16{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}“When is Hashem exalted through justice?” The Talmud answers, “He is exalted during 
the ten days from Rosh Hashana until Yom Kippur.”—Berachos 12b\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*17>}17{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}When saying “the King, the Holy One” bear in mind, that it is impossible for a human 
being to conceive or imagine His holiness.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*18>}18{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}You have designated us for a specific task and destiny.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*19>}19{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Your love for us was made manifest when You took us out of Egypt.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*20>}20{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}We were exalted above all tongues when we received the Torah at Sinai, when Hashem 
chose our tongue as the most suited language for the revelation of His Torah.—S.R. Hirsch\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*21>}21{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}By giving us Your Torah, You have become our King and so have permitted us to draw 
near to You as Your loyal servants.—S.R. Hirsch\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*22>}22{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}By shaping all of our life’s values and by Your evident guidance of our destinies, You have 
made us the bearers of Your Name.—S.R. Hirsch\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*23>}23{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}In the Torah, (Vayikra 23:24) Rosh Hashana is described with the words {\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'e9\'c4\'e4\'c0\'e9\'c6\'e4 \'ec\'c8\'eb\'c6\'ed \'f9\'d1\'c7\'e1\'cc\'c8\'fa\'e5\zwj\'c9\'ef \'e6\'c4\'eb\'c0\'f8\'e5\zwj\'c9\'ef 
\'fa\'cc\'c0\'f8\'e5\'cc\'f2\'c8\'e4{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch . We are thus taught that it is both a day of {\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'e6\'c4\'eb\'cc\'c8\'f8\'e5\zwj\'c9\'ef{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch , remembrance, and {\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'fa\'cc\'c0\'f8\'e5\'cc\'f2\'c8\'e4{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch , a day of sounding 
