Since we are not that righteous, Hashem shields and delivers us even though we have no 
merit.—Siach Yitzchak\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*64>}64{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Alternatively: “Affect mankind to the end of earthly time.” —Avudraham\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*65>}65{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}“Your Torah” means the basic concepts of the Torah itself, and “Your word” refers to 
ethical concepts, derived from events described in the Torah and by the Prophets.—Siach 
Yitzchak\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*66>}66{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}We refer to Hashem as First and Last only in order to preclude the notion that anything 
existed before Him, and to repudiate the idea that there is an end to His existence. We do not 
assert that He has a beginning or a fixed term.—Kuzari\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*67>}67{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}See Shemos 4:22.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*68>}68{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Hashem humbled the Egyptians who were haughty and raised high the Jews who had 
been lowly captives in Egypt.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*69>}69{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Hashem also helps those who are spiritually impoverished.—Rabbi Yehuda ben Yakar\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*70>}70{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Intrinsically.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*71>}71{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}By others.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*72>}72{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}As it is said, “And a redeemer will come to Tziyon and to those of Yaakov who repent of 
their transgression, said Adonoy” (Yeshaya 59:20).\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*73>}73{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}While Hashem is always referred to as the Redeemer of Yisrael, this blessing utilizes the 
past tense, “Who redeemed Yisrael,” as it refers specifically to our redemption from 
Egypt.—Tzelosa d’Avraham\par
{\highlight7 @sn}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}Our faith in the Redeemer of Yisrael Who redeemed us from Egypt, and our hope that He will 
redeem us from exile, give us the spiritual energy and courage to stand before Him, to pray and 
beseech Him for our needs, as we proceed to the Amidah.—Yesodos haTefillah\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*74>}74{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Rabbi Yonasan Eibschitz in his sefer, Yaaros Devash, explains that upon reflecting in 
Whose Presence he is about to pray, man should be so overwhelmed with awe and trepidation 
that he is unable to open his lips. He therefore prefaces his prayer by beseeching Hashem, to open 
his lips, asking His help to be able to pray in His Presence.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*75>}75{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Because these are days of judgment and our lives hang in the balance, we pray to Hashem 
