deep in our hearts how little and how poorly we have prepared ourselves. Thus our Sages 
ordained that we open the prayers with the word {\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'e5\'cc\'e1\'c0\'eb\'c5\'ef{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch  recalling the words of Esther; therewith 
shattering our delusions of spiritual complacency, and causing us to bow before Him with broken 
hearts and tearfilled eyes.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*88>}88{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}The word {\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'fa\'cc\'c5\'ef{\highlight7 {\ltrch @hh}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch  implies {\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'ee\'c7\'fa\'cc\'c8\'f0\'c8\'e4{\highlight7 {\ltrch @hh}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch , a gift. We ask Hashem to grant us the feeling of reverence for 
Him, as a gift, knowing how difficult it is to attain such a high level of reverence completely on 
our own (Siach Yitzchak).\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*89>}89{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}The word {\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'ee\'c7\'f2\'c2\'f9\'d2\'c6\'e9\'ea\'c8{\highlight7 {\ltrch @hh}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch , lit., Your works, indicates that which has attained or is near perfection. 
Thus Yisrael is called His works since we have accepted His Kingship and His Torah which is the 
fulfillment of Hashem’s creation (Siach Yitzchak).\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*90>}90{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}All you have created, {\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'f9\'d1\'c6\'e1\'cc\'c8\'f8\'c8\'e0\'fa\'c8{\highlight7 {\ltrch @hh}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch , indicates that which has not attained its fulfillment, thus we 
ask Hashem to cast His dread even on those people who have not yet accepted His Divine 
Kingdom (Siach Yitzchak).\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*91>}91{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}The nation of Yisrael will fear You.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*92>}92{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}The nations of the world will finally prostrate themselves before You, i.e. submit to You 
and accept the yoke of Your Kingship.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*93>}93{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Once all of Your works and created beings have submitted themselves to Your rule and 
formed a single bond to do Your will, the honor of Yisrael will be established and raised to new 
heights. It will then be apparent to all that Yisrael alone carried the yoke of Hashem’s kingdom 
throughout the bitter years of exile, giving Him obedience despite its suffering and persecution 
and the taunts of those who cynically asked, “Where is Your God?” (Etz Yosef).\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*94>}94{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Those who fear Hashem will then be praiseworthy in the eyes of all men.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*95>}95{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Men will no longer consider as ridiculous those who seek Hashem and search for ways to 
serve Him.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*96>}96{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Those who wait upon Him will no longer be subdued but will voice their convictions 
freely.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*97>}97{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}See Tehillim 132:17. The climax of this spiritual renaissance will be the restoration of our 
people to our land under the scepter of the Moshiach, descendant of Dovid, the anointed of 
Hashem.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*98>}98{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}The entire universe was created for the sake of Yisrael in order that Hashem’s Divine 
Influence be attached to it. This essence (Yisrael) was created for the sake of an even more 
treasured essence, namely the prophets and the pious among them. This gradation forms the basis 
of the sequence of the Rosh Hashana±Yom Kippur prayers: “Grant that Your awe be upon all that 
You have made,” is the first prayer. It is followed by, “Grant honor to Your people,” and finally 
by “the righteous will see this and rejoice.” Thus the righteous and pious are the purpose and 
fulfillment of the entire creation, the true reason for celebrating these holy days (Fundamentals of 
Kuzari, page 59).\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*99>}99{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Our plea to Hashem is, “let Your rule become evident in all Your glory.” For we know that 
Hashem has reigned supreme at all times; it is only man who, until now, has failed to recognize 
Hashem’s rule and render Him homage. We now pray that man will at long last come to know 
Hashem’s eternal, universal sovereignty and pay it the tribute of unreserved obedience (S.R. 
Hirsch).\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*100>}100{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}According to Avudraham this classification refers to the very wicked who have never 
fulfilled a commandment, but who nevertheless have breath in their nostrils. Let them also 
proclaim on the Day of Judgment, that You, Hashem of Yisrael are King!\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*101>}101{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Even as Hashem Himself is forever true, and even as His word, the Torah and the promise 
revealed to us are eternally true and unalterable, so too our own service to Him should be true, 
unswerving and constant. For this purpose we pray for {\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'e8\'c7\'e4\'c2\'f8\'c7\'fa \'e4\'c7\'ec\'cc\'c5\'e1{\highlight7 {\ltrch @hh}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch , purity of heart. We must cleanse 
and purify our hearts of every passion and impulse that might tempt us to transgress the law or 
that might stand in the way of our serving Hashem (S.R. Hirsch).\par
{\highlight7 <CH21>}{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*1>}1{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}This refers to the words of Hashem, as revealed through His prophets.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*2>}2{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}See Devarim 32:9. “Yaakov is the bond of His inheritance ({\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'e9\'f2\'f7\'c9\'e1 \'e7\'e1\'ec \'f0\'e7\'ec\'fa\'e5\zwj\'c9{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch ).”\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*3>}3{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}See Zecharyah 9:12\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*4>}4{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}See Maseches Shabbos 63a\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*5>}5{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}See Malachi 3:16\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*6>}6{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}See Tehillim 69:32\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*7>}7{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}This refers to the {\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'ee\'c6\'ec\'c6\'ea\'c0 \'e4\'c7\'ee\'c8\'f9\'d1\'c4\'e9\'e7\'c7{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch , the Moshiach King.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*8>}8{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}We ask Hashem to sound the shofar of redemption, calling our dispersed brethren to gather 
on His holy mountain.—Mateh Levi\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*9>}9{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}This refers to those who do evil against against our people.—Mateh Levi\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*10>}10{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}This refers to the quickness of Hashem’s punishment of the wicked. See Ibn Ezra to 
Nachum 1:3.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*11>}11{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}See Amos 4:7\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*12>}12{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}See Tehillim 19:3. The daily renewal of the activities of creation, beginning with sunrise, 
stir mankind to proclaim Hashem’s praises.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*13>}13{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}The word {\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'f9\'d1\'c6\'f7\'c6\'e8{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch  actually means serenity or stability. The earth is viewed as a stable planet.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*14>}14{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}The word {\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'f0\'c9\'f2\'c7\'ed{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch , pleasantness refers to the Torah “whose ways are ways of pleasantness, {\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'e3\'c0\'f8\'c8\'eb\'c6\'e9\'e4\'c8 
\'e3\'c7\'f8\'c0\'eb\'c5\'e9 \'f0\'c9\'f2\'c7\'ed{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch .”\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*15>}15{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}The nation of Yisrael is referred to as the “leaders of song.” This is based on the Talmud, 
“the angels on high do not sing Hashem’s praises until Yisrael has completed its prayers.” See 
Maseches Chulin 91b.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*16>}16{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}See Yeshaya 28:5\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*17>}17{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}They are the angels.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*18>}18{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Yeshaya 6:3\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*19>}19{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Yechezkel 3:12\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*20>}20{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Tehillim 146:10\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*21>}21{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}The Jewish People are referred to in Scripture as Hashem’s slaves (Vayikra 25:42), and as 
His children (Devarim 14:1). Thus we say to Him, “If we are Your children, we beseech You as 
our Father; if we are Your slaves, we implore You as our Master and King. Contrary to the view 
that Hashem the Father is so full of love for His children that He permits the wanton breaking of 
His commandments to go unpunished, Judaism knows that Hashem the King must be feared and 
His laws must be obeyed. There are times when a father is unable to do what he would like for 
his children because of physical or financial limitations. On the other hand, a king has the power 
to do anything for his subjects if he should so desire. We cry out to Hashem—You are our Father 
and You desire to help us—You are our King and You have the power to help us!\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*22>}22{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Despite our physical banishment and spiritual estrangement—the result of our sins—we 
still have none other than Hashem to guide our lives and to shape our destiny.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*23>}23{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}See Yechezkel 36.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*24>}24{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Having just asked that our sins be forgiven and that our transgressions be removed from 
before His eyes, what are we asking for now? Our earlier pleas were for forgiveness of those sins 
we committed ourselves. But there are sins for which we are held accountable even though we do 
not commit them ourselves. One possibility is that of watching while others sin when we may 
have been able to prevent it. (Chazal say {\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'eb\'cc\'c8\'ec \'e9\'c4\'f9\'d2\'c0\'f8\'c8\'e0\'c5\'ec \'f2\'c2\'f8\'c5\'e1\'c4\'e9\'ef \'e6\'c6\'e4 \'ec\'c8\'e6\'c6\'e4{\highlight7 {\ltrch @hh}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch . A guarantor is one who countersigns 
a debt note, undertaking to pay if the borrower defaults. Thus we ask Hashem to erase all our 
notes of obligation whether as borrower or guarantor. In all instances He is the Extender of credit.) 
Thus we beseech Hashem to erase the records of our guilt in those instances.—Siach Yitzchak\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*25>}25{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Many repent out of their fear of Hashem. Others repent out of their love for Him. We 
beseech Hashem to bring us back in “wholehearted” repentance motivated by love, the most 
perfect form of penitence.—Etz Yosef\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*26>}26{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}We beseech Hashem to heal both the spiritually ill as well as the physically ill. We ask, 
therefore, for a “complete” healing for the sick among us.—Etz Yosef\par
{\highlight7 <CH22>}{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*1>}1{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}When saying the words, “{\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'ec\'c0\'ee\'c7\'f2\'c7\'f0\'c0\'ea\'c8 \'e0\'c6\'ec\'c9\'f7\'c4\'e9\'ed \'e7\'c7\'e9\'c4\'e9\'ed{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch ,” “for Your sake living God,” you might offer this 
silent prayer: Master of the Universe, because we believe in the absolute unity of Your Name, that 
You alone are the living God, and there is nothing besides You, it is fitting and proper that You 
inscribe us in the Book of Life.—Yesod V’shoresh HaAvodah\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*2>}2{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}The Divine deliverance of our people will not come about in a sudden, dramatic fashion, but 
rather as a gradual development, as a plant that sprouts forth in stages.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*3>}3{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}The Chasam Sofer says that {\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'e6\'e5\zwj\'c9\'eb\'c5\'f8 \'e9\'c0\'f6\'e5\'cc\'f8\'c8\'e9\'e5 \'ec\'c0\'e7\'c7\'e9\'c4\'e9\'ed \'e1\'cc\'c0\'f8\'c7\'e7\'c2\'ee\'c4\'e9\'ed{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch  does not mean that we ask Hashem to 
remember us for life in His mercy, but rather that He grant us {\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'e7\'c7\'e9\'c4\'e9\'ed \'f9\'d1\'c6\'ec \'f8\'c7\'e7\'c2\'ee\'c4\'e9\'ed{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch , a life of mercy, a life 
in which we will exemplify the quality and virtue of compassion.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*4>}4{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}When saying these sentences, bear in mind these words: “How long has Your great, sacred 
Name been desecrated among the nations as they taunt us, asking, “Where is Your God? Why 
doesn’t He come to your aid?” Therefore, let Your awe be upon all Your works, Your dread upon 
all You have created, so they may all know there is no God but You, and thus will Your Name be 
exalted and sanctified even among the nations.—Yesod V’Shoresh HaAvodah\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*5>}5{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}The ultimate sanctification of Hashem’s great and Holy Name over the nation of Yisrael will 
have a tremendous impact on all peoples and will result in their spiritual uplifting for they will 
be inspired to fear Hashem, and subject themselves to His rule.—R’ Moshe Chaim Luzzato, 
(Yalkut Yedeos HaEmes)\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*6>}6{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}The Divine inspiration of Hashem, Who is One, the Unity par excellence, can only be 
experienced by an entity, united, in a single cause. The nation of Yisrael, though composed of 
individuals, is nevertheless a unit, bound by its singular belief in Hashem and Torah. Thus we are 
referred to as {\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'e2\'e5\'c9\'e9 \'e0\'c6\'e7\'c8\'e3 \'e1\'cc\'c8\'e0\'c8\'f8\'c6\'f5{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch  one nation in the land, and as such, we are capable of receiving and 
retaining the Divine influence. The nations of the world however are many, and the diversity 
within each nation is great. In their present status they are incapable of experiencing the Divine 
inspiration. We pray, therefore, for the time when they will attach themselves to the nation of 
Yisrael, and recognize the superiority of our moral and spiritual values. Then, they will attain a 
level of unity and be capable of receiving a degree of Divine enlightenment. This is the intent of 
our prayer, “and may they all form a single band.”—R’ Moshe Chaim Luzzato, Ibid.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*7>}7{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Those who understand and recognize the mysterious ways in which Hashem rules the 
world, realize that despite superficial events that seem to indicate otherwise, Hashem’s rule is 
indisputable and all powerful. Thus we declare our firm belief in His rulership and His 
strength.—R’ Moshe Chaim Luzzato, Ibid\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*8>}8{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Despite our status as a chosen and holy people, only when the entire world reaches its 
ultimate perfection, will we achieve our ultimate goal. Thus only after Hashem’s kingdom is 
revealed in the world, and good triumphs over evil, will we reach our maximum potential and 
thereby bask in His glory. This is our prayer, “grant honor, Almighty, to Your people.”—R. 
Moshe Chaim Luzzato, Ibid.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*9>}9{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}The only setting for this glorious fulfillment is in the Holy Land—there in the chosen land, 
will the chosen people experience its true spiritual fulfillment, under the leadership of the king, a 
descendant of the chosen house of royalty, the house of Dovid.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*10>}10{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}The literal translation of {\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'f7\'c6\'f8\'c6\'ef{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch  is horn, but it is often translated pride because the horn is the 
pride of the animal.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*11>}11{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}According to Pri Tzadik, the righteous are those who serve Hashem with meticulous 
observance of Torah and Mitzvos even without experiencing the inner joy and radiance of serving 
Him. They will therefore be privileged to see and rejoice in the time to come.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*12>}12{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}The upright are those whose hearts are filled with joy at serving their Creator through the 
fulfillment of Torah and Mitzvos. They will therefore be jubilant at the revelation of Hashem’s 
kingdom.—Pri Tzadik\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*13>}13{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}The pious are those whose attachment to Hashem is so great that they serve Him in ways 
which are even beyond and above the precisely ordained commands of the Torah. They will be 
privileged to exult in joyous song at the time to come.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*14>}14{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}The terms, injustice, all wickedness and rule of evil refer to Amalek, the archenemy of the 
Jewish people and of Hashem. Its name and memory will ultimately be obliterated from the 
earth.—R’ Moshe Chaim Luzzato\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*15>}15{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}And thus will begin the kingdom of Hashem on earth, which is the ultimate goal of man’s 
development through the ages and which centers forever in Yerushalayim and Tziyon.—S.R. 
Hirsch\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*16>}16{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}“When is Hashem exalted through justice?” The Talmud answers, “He is exalted during 
the ten days from Rosh Hashana until Yom Kippur.”—Berachos 12b\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*17>}17{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}When saying “the King, the Holy One” bear in mind, that it is impossible for a human 
being to conceive or imagine His holiness.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*18>}18{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}You have designated us for a specific task and destiny.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*19>}19{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}Your love for us was made manifest when You took us out of Egypt.\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*20>}20{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}We were exalted above all tongues when we received the Torah at Sinai, when Hashem 
chose our tongue as the most suited language for the revelation of His Torah.—S.R. Hirsch\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <*21>}21{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}By giving us Your Torah, You have become our King and so have permitted us to draw 
near to You as Your loyal servants.—S.R. Hirsch\par
